It was the culmination of three years of fighting and 21 days of intense peace negotiations on a US air base in Dayton, Ohio.
The presidents of Serbia, Bosnia and Croatia signed the Dayton Peace Accords and established the blueprint for Bosnia-Herzegovina.

Al Jazeera’s Rory Challands reports from Sarajevo.

Trump says no decision has been made on whether Washington will send a representative to the upcoming Paris talks involving Ukraine, France, Germany, and the UK. He repeats earlier statements from the White House, saying attendance will depend on whether there is “a good chance” for progress.

Trump also warns that prolonged tensions could escalate into a “third world war”, stressing the need to resolve the conflict and “save a lot of lives.”

On Gaza, Trump provides little clarity when asked about reports that a US general may lead a stabilisation force. He instead asserts that “real peace in the Middle East” exists with the backing of dozens of countries, though he gives no timeline for the Gaza stabilization plan.

Al Jazeera’s Mike Hanna joins live from Washington.

Senate Democrats and Republicans presented competing health care bills for a vote on Thursday—and both of them failed to get enough votes to advance. The Republican plan aimed to replace those subsidies with money for health savings accounts.
